WEBVTT

00:07.591 --> 00:07.971
Go ahead. Is it ready to go? Well, after we bought 
this car, people come in the yard to see it. Some of

00:16.841 --> 00:18.703
them say it wouldn't last. Some of them thought it 
was all right. But I think we drove it about 10

00:21.827 --> 00:25.150
years.

00:31.177 --> 00:31.998
Is it going? It's going fine. Go ahead. And, of 
course, then they made things to last. They didn't

00:37.443 --> 00:40.528
make it to wear out and go buy a new one the next day. 
And there has been so many things now, though, that

00:40.568 --> 00:48.841
we didn't have then. I can look back in my kitchen.

00:55.772 --> 00:59.678
When I first kept house, everything was hard. I had 
a wood stove. We didn't buy stuff already prepared

01:06.822 --> 01:10.125
to eat. We had to fix it. And now, I think about the 
young generation. All convenience in the world,

01:16.972 --> 01:19.655
they've got it. And I don't know, they don't keep 
house like I did when I was raising my first

01:21.417 --> 01:27.423
children. And washed, I always had help. I always 
had a colored woman to help me. And she washed on the

01:34.150 --> 01:36.272
washboard. and iron with a flat iron, get that iron 
hot. She'd build up a fire out in the yard with wood,

01:42.836 --> 01:51.105
and she'd put the iron in front of that and get it 
hot, and that's the way she ironed. And now they

01:51.525 --> 01:56.391
have electric iron, and everything's 
perma-pressed. Then everything was starched,

01:56.491 --> 01:59.814
stiff as a poker. Things have come a long, long way, 
I can tell you. At last, they have really made it

02:06.847 --> 02:11.893
easy on the housewife. Do you think it's good or 
bad? Well, I'll tell you what. In a way, it's good.

02:20.042 --> 02:21.744
And in a way, it is not. It has made the young 
housewife lazy. Maybe because she doesn't have to

02:26.410 --> 02:28.032
do as much work. She don't have no hard work to do. 
And they have washing machines. And most every,

02:35.517 --> 02:38.520
now I don't like a dryer. Why is that? Is it stop? Can 
I start? Yeah, go ahead. I'll tell you my objection

02:45.566 --> 02:47.708
to a dryer. They burn the clothes, then the clothes 
is not pretty and white. But I'll say this, it may be

02:52.333 --> 02:58.078
because I'm old fashioned. You can't teach hardly 
an old dog new tricks. And for 83 years, in fact, the

03:03.293 --> 03:10.524
seventh day of May, I'll be keeping house 61 years. 
That's quite a long time. And that's a long time to

03:12.867 --> 03:15.251
have to change. Now, I will admit, I've got all 
convenience. Yes, I've got it. And I appreciate it

03:22.101 --> 03:24.264
and I enjoy it. But don't think that I don't think so 
many times of things that I have done or we have

03:25.245 --> 03:32.676
done, rather. Not I myself, but everybody else did 
the same thing. Like what? Well, look, now,

03:39.147 --> 03:44.014
everything, I even have an electric coffee pot. 
You've got electric toaster. You've got

03:46.398 --> 03:53.828
electric, just everything in the world in your 
kitchen now is electric. I used to make my coffee in

03:53.848 --> 03:59.777
a pot, a coffee pot, put it on the stove, and boil 
those grounds, push it off and let it set a while,

04:00.095 --> 04:06.384
and then pour that coffee in another pot. That was 
coffee. Well, now I either use electric

04:07.706 --> 04:12.172
percolator or drippolator. What kind of cooking 
facilities, you know, say stove or oven or

04:13.234 --> 04:19.904
whatever did you have? I had a wood stove. For 
cooking, too? Yes, sir, a wood stove. And don't you

04:24.971 --> 04:29.798
forget it, that that's the best cooking in the 
world on a wood stove. Now everything's cooked

04:30.335 --> 04:33.118
quick, quick. Get it out of the deep freeze and pop 
it in the stove and cook it quick. Did you, back in

04:37.563 --> 04:44.010
your family, when you grew up as a child, how did you 
heat your house? Well, we had fireplaces. Was it

04:46.193 --> 04:48.115
pretty cold up in Tennessee? Oh, in Tennessee, 
people almost, they still have fireplaces there

04:48.135 --> 04:55.323
because they're on account of the weather. Is that 
cold up there? Oh, me, yes, it's cold there. And

05:00.322 --> 05:04.609
they had wood stoves, of course. People now, they 
have modern homes, I understand now, but the

05:05.450 --> 05:11.420
majority of people have fireplaces. Yeah, 
fireplaces are a thing to have anywhere now. Yeah,

05:13.583 --> 05:20.635
fireplaces now, just like even in Texas now, 
people building new homes, they have fireplaces.

05:20.655 --> 05:22.177
Yeah, yeah. Because, and of course, in my day, wood 
was cheap. When I moved to Hearn, we, that old house

05:28.317 --> 05:37.308
that I sold last year, well, there was fireplaces 
there. And then wood got higher and got to where

05:39.170 --> 05:49.462
you'd have to hire it and cut and everything while 
we had it closed up and got gas heaters. I didn't

05:49.482 --> 05:50.884
know there was a fireplace over there. Oh, yeah. It 
was closed up. There was two of them. There was one

05:54.408 --> 05:57.852
in that north bedroom and one in the living room. 
Oh, no. Even my baby girl, we had it closed up. She

06:07.005 --> 06:14.116
don't remember us having fireplace, and she's 
getting on up there herself. Well, times has

06:14.777 --> 06:17.361
changed so much. Another thing with teenagers, 
they congregate at one's house. And they'd play

06:26.317 --> 06:27.979
cards. They'd play dominoes. And they would have a 
record player. And they'd dance. Was it crank

06:37.509 --> 06:38.670
record player? Yeah. It was called a phonograph. 
You had a great big horn. And you'd turn that thing.

06:47.400 --> 06:50.423
And you'd put a record on there. There's records. 
And the children, they didn't think about getting

06:51.713 --> 07:00.725
in a car and riding out yonder, and there wasn't 
always a car wreck and things then. Well, my first

07:01.826 --> 07:06.493
children, I had two sets of children, same mother 
and daddy. The first four were great big children

07:07.794 --> 07:16.506
when I had these four little girls, and they still 
say they're four little girls. And they didn't

07:18.157 --> 07:24.344
study about going, for they had horse and birdie. 
They met at one another's house. And now they don't

07:26.266 --> 07:29.729
go to one another's house. They get in a car and go 
off somewhere and have a car wreck and somebody get

07:30.330 --> 07:34.935
killed. I think that's one thing, the way that 
makes time so hard is the way people let their

07:34.955 --> 07:44.305
children do now. I think they've brought a whole 
lot of it on themselves. by not being economical.

07:50.908 --> 07:54.214
Now, you take this crisis that we're going through 
with gas. There's plenty of gas and plenty of oil.

07:59.802 --> 08:00.944
It's somewhere else. But we have brought it on 
ourselves, a whole lot of it. I'll tell you, the

08:06.593 --> 08:14.826
majority of people have took living for granted 
that I'm supposed to have this. I don't think

08:17.202 --> 08:20.908
that's right, what you're supposed to have. God 
don't owe you nothing. Amen to that. I agree with

08:25.394 --> 08:26.055
you. But a lot of people think so. God owes them a 
living. This is me. Why can't I have that? You can

08:31.283 --> 08:35.149
have it if you work for it, if you're well and can. Of 
course, there's some people that can't. And I'll

08:38.594 --> 08:43.682
tell you another thing that's changed. People 
used to help each other. If a neighbor got sick, I'd

08:48.915 --> 08:57.327
go over and I'd get their clothes, and we'd wash and 
iron them, take them to them. And we used to make

08:58.268 --> 09:00.271
homemade bread. Make a great big pan of homemade 
bread, bake a hen in dressing, and take it to the

09:01.052 --> 09:08.162
family. People now don't do that. They don't love 
one another like they used to. They don't care.

09:14.864 --> 09:17.147
I'll tell you the way the world is now. Just so me and 
mine is the swimming, you can sink.

09:25.296 --> 09:26.918
Oh, there's been lots of changes. What kind of a 
roads facility did you have around here when y'all

09:27.839 --> 09:31.824
first came here? Oh, we had dirt roads. All of them 
were dirt? No paved highways? No. I forgot what

09:38.071 --> 09:43.217
year it was, but I was living on Market Street when 
